Lab 8: Bagging, Random Forest and Boosting

Yangyi Lu

2/28/2020

In this lab, we use spam email dataset to illustrate three classification methods: bagging, random forest and boosting. Spam email dataset is accessible at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/spambase. There are 4601 rows, each row is a vector of length 58, containing information about words in an email. There are 58 columns, 48 of them represent word frequencies, 6 of them represent some character frequencies, 3 of them represent capital letter information and the last column contains the true class labels: 0 for non-spam, 1 for spam.

Load the Spam Dataset

set.seed(1)
dat = read.csv("spambase.data",header = F)

# loading column names
names = read.table("names.txt")
colnames(dat) = names[,1]

# convert class label column to factor variable
dat$spam = factor(dat$spam)
levels(dat$spam) = c("Non-Spam", "Spam")

# spliting training and testing set
n = nrow(dat)
train_id = sample(n,size = floor(n*0.7))
train = dat[train_id,]
test = dat[-train_id,]

Tree Model Revisit

The spam and non-spam individuals in training dataset are balanced enough.

table(train$spam)
## 
## Non-Spam     Spam 
##     1930     1290

The best model for spam email classification task in last lab using tree model is achieved by: 1) splitting based on entropy 2) penalty parameter \(cp = 0.012\) in pruning the tree

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
tree_entropy = rpart(spam ~ ., data = train, parms = list(split = "gini"),
                     method = "class", cp = 0.012)

We next use the fitted tree_entropy model to calculate the training and testing error.

# training error
train_pred = predict(tree_entropy,train,type = "class")
table(train_pred,train$spam)
##           
## train_pred Non-Spam Spam
##   Non-Spam     1834  231
##   Spam           96 1059
train_err = mean(train_pred!=train$spam)
train_err
## [1] 0.1015528
# testing error
test_pred = predict(tree_entropy,test,type = "class")
table(test_pred,test$spam)
##           
## test_pred  Non-Spam Spam
##   Non-Spam      823  107
##   Spam           35  416
test_err = mean(test_pred!=test$spam)
test_err
## [1] 0.102824

Bagging

Here we apply bagging to spam email data, using randomForest package. The exact results obtained in this section may depend on the version of R and the version of the randomForest package installed on your computer.

Recall that bagging is simply a special case of a random forest with \(m=p\), where \(m\) is the number of feature being sampled to build trees and \(p\) is the number of all features. Therefore, the randomForest() function can be used to perform both random forests and bagging. We will perform bagging first as follows:

library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.6-14
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
set.seed(1)
bag_spam = randomForest(spam ~ ., data = train, mtry = ncol(train)-1,
                        importance = TRUE, ntree = 500)
bag_spam
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = spam ~ ., data = train, mtry = ncol(train) -      1, importance = TRUE, ntree = 500) 
##                Type of random forest: classification
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 57
## 
##         OOB estimate of  error rate: 5.62%
## Confusion matrix:
##          Non-Spam Spam class.error
## Non-Spam     1855   75  0.03886010
## Spam          106 1184  0.08217054

How well does this bagging model perform on test set?

bag_test_pred = predict(bag_spam, newdata = test)
table(bag_test_pred, test$spam)
##              
## bag_test_pred Non-Spam Spam
##      Non-Spam      830   47
##      Spam           28  476
bag_test_err = mean(bag_test_pred!=test$spam)
bag_test_err
## [1] 0.05430847

Above result greatly improves the one using single tree based model.

Random Forest

Random forest procedures are identical to bagging except that we only use a fraction of features to grow trees. By default, randomForest() uses \(\sqrt{p}\) variables when building classfication trees. We will try multiple mtry here.

set.seed(1)
rf_spam = randomForest(spam ~ ., data = train, mtry = floor(sqrt(57)),
                       importance = TRUE)
rf_spam
## 
## Call:
##  randomForest(formula = spam ~ ., data = train, mtry = floor(sqrt(57)),      importance = TRUE) 
##                Type of random forest: classification
##                      Number of trees: 500
## No. of variables tried at each split: 7
## 
##         OOB estimate of  error rate: 4.94%
## Confusion matrix:
##          Non-Spam Spam class.error
## Non-Spam     1868   62  0.03212435
## Spam           97 1193  0.07519380

How well does this random forest with mtry around \(8\) model perform on test set?

rf_test_pred = predict(rf_spam, newdata = test)
table(rf_test_pred, test$spam)
##             
## rf_test_pred Non-Spam Spam
##     Non-Spam      832   38
##     Spam           26  485
rf_test_err = mean(rf_test_pred!=test$spam)
rf_test_err
## [1] 0.04634323

Above result improves the bagging model.

Two measures of variable importance are reported. The former is based upon the mean decrease of accuracy in predictions on the out of bag samples when a given variable is excluded from the model. The latter is a measure of the total decrease in node impurity that results from splits over that variable, averaged over all trees.

Plots of these importance measures can be produced using the varImpPlot() function.

varImpPlot(rf_spam)

Above importance plot shows that the terms with five highest score are: exclamation; money; free; capital letters.

Boosting

Here we use gbm package, specifically the gbm() function within it, to fit boosting model for the spam email dataset.

Adaboost

Adaboost builds an additive model by stagewise fitting using the exponential loss function. Here we set distribution="adaboost" in gbm(). By default, the shrinkage parameter \(\mu\) is set to \(0.1\), which controls the speed of boosting. \[f(x) = \sum_{m=1}^M\mu\alpha_mT_m(x)\] We will try different shrinkage parameters to see how this affects the prediction performance.

In gbm, we need to ensure that the outcome variable is represented by \(0\) or \(1\). So we first convert Spam and Non-spam to \(1\) and \(0\).

Depth 3, tree 5000: early stopping can avoid overfitting

library(gbm)
## Loaded gbm 2.1.5
set.seed(1)
train$spam = ifelse(train$spam=="Spam",1,0)
test$spam = ifelse(test$spam=="Spam",1,0)
ada_spam = gbm(spam~., data = train, distribution = "adaboost", n.trees = 5000,
               interaction.depth = 3)
summary(ada_spam)

Try small shrinkage parameter: \(0.01\): updating slowly helps training.

Shrinkage parameter controls the speed of model updating, lets now try a small shrinkage parameter, but keep the number of trees unchanged.

set.seed(1)
ada_spam_1 = gbm(spam~., data = train, distribution = "adaboost", 
                 n.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 3, shrinkage = 0.01)
ada_pred_response_1 = predict(ada_spam_1, newdata = test, n.trees = 1000, 
                              type = "response")
ada_pred_1 = ifelse(ada_pred_response_1>0.5,1,0)
table(ada_pred_1,test$spam)
##           
## ada_pred_1   0   1
##          0 826  52
##          1  32 471
ada_err_1 = mean(ada_pred_1!=test$spam)
ada_err_1
## [1] 0.06082549

The above results show that only changing the shrinkage parameter to be smaller hurts the prediction performance. The reason is we keep the number of updates unchanged, but reducing the amount of update at every iteration. So when we finish fitting all the 1000 trees, the model may still not converge.

Use more weak predictors (number of trees) for small shrinkage parameter \(0.01\)

Since our shrinkage is \(0.01\) here, comparing to the first adaboost model which uses \(0.1\), the udpating amount at every iteration shrinkages by 10 times. Thus, we will use \(10000\) trees instead of only \(1000\) to keep the same amount of total updating.

set.seed(1)
ada_spam_2 = gbm(spam~., data = train, distribution = "adaboost", 
                 n.trees = 10000, interaction.depth = 3, shrinkage = 0.01)
ada_pred_response_2 = predict(ada_spam_2, newdata = test, n.trees = 10000, 
                              type = "response")
ada_pred_2 = ifelse(ada_pred_response_2>0.5,1,0)
table(ada_pred_2,test$spam)
##           
## ada_pred_2   0   1
##          0 827  31
##          1  31 492
ada_err_2 = mean(ada_pred_2!=test$spam)
ada_err_2
## [1] 0.044895

We observe that when updating the model slower, which means using smaller shrinkage parameter, increasing the number of trees can improve the prediction performance.

Boosting with logistic regression loss

Here we use gbm() function with distribution = "bernoulli".

set.seed(1)
logit_spam = gbm(spam~., data = train, distribution = "bernoulli", 
                 n.trees = 1000, interaction.depth = 3, shrinkage = 0.1)
logit_pred_response = predict(logit_spam, newdata = test, n.trees = 1000, 
                              type = "response")
logit_pred = ifelse(logit_pred_response>0.5,1,0)
table(logit_pred,test$spam)
##           
## logit_pred   0   1
##          0 825  33
##          1  33 490
logit_err = mean(logit_pred!=test$spam)
logit_err
## [1] 0.04779146

The prediction performance is similar to adaboost. We summarize some representative models testing error results in below:

  1. tree: 0.1028
  2. bagging: 0.0543
  3. best rf: 0.0456
  4. best adaboost: 0.0449
  5. boosting with logit loss: 0.0478
